{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1778260807,"nonce":"WzkhM/gLuDOfbmm3jUM/n6VGp4g=","title":"Replicate C\u0026S 2019 analytical LQG vs H∞ Riccati directly","message":"Stage 0 in the proposed regulator-coupling / decoupling-chain programme (exploration, not committed). This is the first thing to run before any training.\n\n**Question.** On the C\u0026S 2019 regime (cs_faithful_pointmass, k=0.1, τ=0.06, m=1.0), does an LQG Riccati controller (γ → ∞, no disturbance) produce a different Δv signature than the H∞ Riccati (γ ≈ γ*)? This replicates C\u0026S's Fig 1b/1e analytical baseline using our own solver infrastructure, establishing a clean ground truth before touching any training.\n\n**Approach.** Extend src/rlrmp/analysis/hinf_riccati.py with an LQG (no-disturbance / γ → ∞) Riccati solver alongside the existing H∞ solver. On the cs_faithful_pointmass regime, simulate both controllers from rest at p=−0.15, target=0, using the C\u0026S Eq. 15 cost schedule (Q_t ∝ (t/N)^6, 600 ms horizon, 10 ms steps). Compare forward velocity profiles and Δv (signed, projected on reach axis per f90bf74 convention).\n\n**Success / falsification.** LQG should produce Δv ≈ 0 (no disturbance, no reason to inflate velocity). H∞ at γ close to γ* should produce Δv \u003e 0. If H∞ and LQG give the same Δv, the cost schedule — not disturbance rejection — is the dominant driver and the decoupling story needs to be reframed from stage 1 onward.\n\n**Cross-refs.** synthesis.md §4.2 (C\u0026S Eq. 15 schedule), §5.4 (current analytical +1.0% / +10.8% numbers). Existing H∞ solver: src/rlrmp/analysis/hinf_riccati.py. Training-methods coord c99ad9d.","files":null}]}